      "content": "i get the \"geopolitical landscape\" argument, but that's such a convenient way to brush over the massive discrepancies. it’s not just about money, it’s about the sheer volume of declassified documents that seem to leave gaps exactly where the most interesting data should be. if we assume for a second that the \"boring routine\" was the actual cover, it would explain why the skepticism was so heavily baked into the culture. even if you don't \"believe\" it, can you at least look at it from a historical analytical standpoint—how would a massive information suppression campaign actually work in a way that looks like a natural decline in interest?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
